**THE DALLAS HERALD**

  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------
  *Dallas, Texas*         **Wednesday, October    *Five Cents*
                          14, 1914**              

  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------

**WIDOW OF PROMINENT BUSINESSMAN**

**FOUND DEAD AT HOME**

*Mrs. Robert Hartley Succumbs to Apparent Overdose; Had Been in
Declining Health*

***By Dorothy Ann Prescott, Staff Writer***

Margaret Anne Hartley, 38, widow of the late Robert Hartley, was found
dead at her residence on Elm Street on Thursday morning. The Dallas
County coroner has ruled the death an accidental overdose of laudanum, a
tincture of opium commonly prescribed for nervous conditions.

Mrs. Hartley had been in declining health since the death of her husband
in March of 1910. Friends and neighbors described her as increasingly
withdrawn in recent months, rarely seen outside the home. She had been
treated at the Timberlawn Sanatorium on multiple occasions over the past
several years for what physicians described as exhaustion and nervous
prostration.

Dr. Franklin Moss, who attended Mrs. Hartley at Timberlawn, confirmed
that she had struggled with a dependence on laudanum following her
husband's death. "She suffered greatly after the loss of Mr. Hartley,"
Dr. Moss stated. "The medication provided her some relief, but it is a
cruel remedy. The line between comfort and catastrophe is a thin one."

Mrs. Hartley is survived by two young children, who have been placed in
the care of family relatives. The names of the children are being
withheld at the request of the family.

The Hartley family was once among the most prominent in Dallas business
circles. Robert Hartley co-founded the successful toy manufacturing firm
Thoreson & Hartley Toys before his own death in 1910, which was ruled a
suicide. Friends of the family expressed sorrow but little surprise at
the news of Mrs. Hartley's passing.

*"She never recovered from Robert's death," said one neighbor, who asked
not to be identified. "It was as though she lost everything that night
--- not just her husband, but whatever was holding her together."*

Funeral services will be held Monday at 10 a.m. at Calvary Baptist
Church. Burial will follow at Oakland Cemetery.

**COTTON PRICES HOLD STEADY**

Cotton futures closed unchanged yesterday at 12.4 cents per pound on the
New Orleans exchange. Traders attributed the calm to favorable weather
across East Texas and steady demand from Northern mills. The Dallas
Cotton Exchange reported 4,200 bales received at local warehouses this
week, slightly below seasonal averages.

**CITY TO PAVE OAK LAWN AVENUE**

The Dallas City Commission voted Thursday to approve the paving of Oak
Lawn Avenue from Lemmon Avenue north to the city limits. Commissioner J.
B. Adoue stated the work would commence in early November pending
availability of materials. Residents along the route have petitioned for
the improvement for more than two years.

**ELECTRIC STREETCAR SERVICE EXPANDED**

The Dallas Railway & Terminal Co. announced an extension of electric
streetcar service along Commerce Street, with new stops at Lamar and at
the corner of Ervay. Service is expected to begin by month's end. Fare
remains five cents.
